  Appendix 4  13 
B.  Medium-term Financial Management Strategy (MTFMS) Component 
1.  Public Financial Management Expert (international, 5 person-months) 
7.  The international public financial management (PFM) expert will help the MTFMS working 
group  to  develop  and  socialize  the  MTFMS.  In  addition  to  appropriate  academic  and/or 
professional qualifications, the expert will have at least 10 years of PFM experience obtained 
across a broad range of planning, budgeting, accounting, and monitoring activities, and will be a 
specialist in facilitating and recording strategic discussions and developing strategic plans for 
institutions in developing countries. PNG experience is essential, as is a broad understanding of 
the strengths and weaknesses of differing PFM reform approaches in developing countries and the 
ability to work effectively at all levels. The international PFM expert will be the team leader for the 
MTFMS component and will coordinate the national PFM expert’s work. The PFM expert will report 
to the deputy secretary of finance.  

8.  The international PFM expert will help the MTFMS working group and sponsor group to 
develop an agreed MTFMS, which will include  
(i)  a statement of the ultimate objectives of the whole PFM cycle, together with a 
roadmap showing how these objectives can be achieved over the period of the 
strategy through the appropriate phasing and sequencing of activities; 
(ii)  leadership and management arrangements, including monitoring and oversight; 
(iii)  reviews  of  PFM  responsibilities  of  institutions  and  officers  at  different  levels  of 
government; 
(iv)  incentives, rewards, and sanctions underpinning these roles and responsibilities; 
(v)  recommendations for changes to legislative and regulatory frameworks; 
(vi)  recommendations  for  developing  information  and  communications  technology 
infrastructure, including ownership and maintenance; 
(vii)  a change-management program for MTFMS implementation; 
(viii)  consideration of human resource implications, including development requirements 
and a training needs analysis; 
(ix)  an analysis of risks; 
(x)  an MTFMS communications and public relations program and dissemination plan; 
(xi)  time-bound action plans and indicative costs of strategy implementation; and  
(xii)  monitoring indicators using the performance-management framework for PEFA PFM. 

9.  The PFM expert’s inputs will be provided intermittently to coincide with key steps in the 
development of the MTFMS. Prior to the consultant commencing work, the MTFMS working group 
will have reviewed relevant background literature and formed preliminary ideas. The consultant will 
help the MTFMS working group to  
(i)  identify  stakeholder  groups,  including  national  and  sub-national  government 
agencies, civil society, and development partners, and consult with them at relevant 
times throughout the development of the strategy, including in workshops;  
(ii)  form  working  sub-groups  to  specialize  in  specific  areas  where  improvement  is 
needed; 
(iii)  undertake a PEFA PFM assessment, which will provide the basis for monitoring and 
evaluating achievement of MTFMS objectives; 
(iv)  produce  working  papers  documenting  and  assessing  strategic  options  for 
improvement in each specific area, showing institutional responsibilities, constraints, 
ongoing reforms, impacts, benefits, costs, risks, phasing, and sequencing issues;  
(v)  Ensure that the strategies selected for each specific area form a consistent whole;  
(vi)  report regularly to, and take guidance from, the steering committee;  
(vii)  plan the dissemination of the final approved strategy; and
